02:26.700 --> 02:29.180
<i>Yes, ma'am.</i>
<i>How are you doing this afternoon?</i>

02:29.300 --> 02:31.428
<i>Is this Rose Hill?</i>

02:31.540 --> 02:33.986
<i>This is Ed Couch.</i>

02:34.100 --> 02:36.387
<i>I'm Vesta Adcock's nephew.</i>

02:36.500 --> 02:38.582
<i>I need to get up there and see her,</i>

02:38.700 --> 02:42.102
<i>but I'm gonna be a little bit late.
I'll tell you what, I'm lost out here.</i>

02:42.220 --> 02:44.951
<i>We're off the Alabama Interstate,
but I don't know where.</i>

03:19.900 --> 03:21.629
Did you hear that?

03:21.740 --> 03:23.663
What?

03:23.780 --> 03:25.703
The train.

03:25.820 --> 03:27.743
No. I didn't hear no train.

03:29.860 --> 03:31.783
Oh, nothing, I guess.

03:32.900 --> 03:35.141
- Where's Whistle Stop on the map?
- I can't find it.

03:36.260 --> 03:39.104
Why did you tell me to turn right
ten miles back there?

03:41.980 --> 03:45.302
God, you've got a negative sense of direction,
honey.

03:45.420 --> 03:47.343
I'm sorry.

03:47.460 --> 03:51.146
Oh, Ed. Your aunt's
gonna be so disappointed we're late.

03:52.260 --> 03:55.662
I know she's been looking forward to this visit
all week long,

03:55.780 --> 03:57.703
bless her sweet little old heart.

04:03.340 --> 04:05.741
Hey, how's my sweet Auntie V this afternoon?

04:05.860 --> 04:07.783
Remember us?

04:08.900 --> 04:12.621
<i>- Don't you look pretty?
- We've brought you something especially.</i>

04:14.740 --> 04:16.868
<i>Don't you know Evelyn loves you?</i>

04:18.060 --> 04:22.190
Honey, I guess it'd be better
if you just wait out here for me, or something.

04:22.300 --> 04:24.223
- I'll get all this stuff.
- Well, if...

04:24.340 --> 04:26.069
If you think it's best.

04:26.180 --> 04:28.103
Yeah, I do, this time. OK?

04:29.220 --> 04:31.268
Have a nice day, Aunt Vesta.

04:31.380 --> 04:33.621
<i>Don't you pitch a fit like that</i>

04:45.140 --> 04:47.711
Did you know they took my gall bladder out?

04:47.820 --> 04:50.346
Oh... No, I didn't.

04:50.460 --> 04:52.383
<i>Oh, yes.</i>

04:52.500 --> 04:54.707
<i>It's still in the hospital in a jar.</i>

04:56.420 --> 04:58.343
I guess that's where they keep them.

04:58.460 --> 05:00.383
I guess.

05:01.500 --> 05:07.428
When I was in the hospital, the nurse gave me
one of them Fleet enemas they're so fond of.

05:07.540 --> 05:09.986
Mrs. Cleo Threadgoode.

05:10.100 --> 05:12.023
82-year-old widow, imagine that.

05:13.140 --> 05:15.142
Actually, everybody calls me Ninny.

05:16.260 --> 05:18.501
Of course, I'm just visiting here.

05:19.620 --> 05:21.861
Did you ever have one of them Fleet enemas?

05:22.940 --> 05:24.669
Um...

05:24.780 --> 05:26.509
Well...

05:26.620 --> 05:27.587
No.

05:27.700 --> 05:29.623
You'd remember it.

05:30.740 --> 05:33.789
Me and my friend Mrs. Otis
come from Whistle Stop.

05:33.900 --> 05:36.506
You ever been to Whistle Stop?

05:36.620 --> 05:39.271
Why, yes. I just passed by there today.

05:39.380 --> 05:43.271
<i>She's lived down the street from me
for 30 years or more.</i>

05:44.700 --> 05:46.589
After her son died,

05:46.700 --> 05:49.988
her daughter-in-law had a fit for her
to come live here at the nursing home,

05:50.100 --> 05:51.750
and they asked me to come with her

05:51.860 --> 05:53.191
and be her roommate.

05:53.300 --> 05:57.385
Mrs. Otis don't know it, but I'm going back home
just as soon as she gets settled in good.

05:59.500 --> 06:02.106
Does the name Idgie Threadgoode ring a bell?

06:02.220 --> 06:04.143
Um...

06:04.260 --> 06:06.183
No, ma'am. I don't think so.

06:06.300 --> 06:08.223
You'd remember her.

06:09.380 --> 06:12.589
You see, I was practically adopted
by the Threadgoode family.

06:12.700 --> 06:15.226
- I married her brother Cleo.
- Oh. Uh-huh.

06:15.340 --> 06:19.709
Idgie and her friend Ruth
ran the Whistle Stop Café.

06:21.860 --> 06:24.466
Idgie was a character, all right.

06:25.580 --> 06:31.303
<i>But how anybody could have thought
she murdered that man is beyond me.</i>

06:31.420 --> 06:33.627
I beg your pardon?

06:33.740 --> 06:36.550
You sit and relax awhile.
I'll tell you all about it.

06:36.660 --> 06:38.583
Oh, now, let's see...

06:39.860 --> 06:43.103
I remember the day
they pulled that truck up out of the river.

06:44.220 --> 06:46.143
<i>That same rainy summer day,</i>

06:46.260 --> 06:52.905
<i>Idgie Threadgoode was arrested for the murder
of the owner of that truck, Frank Bennett.</i>

06:56.980 --> 07:02.703
I guess to understand Idgie, you'd have to start
way back with her brother Buddy.

07:03.980 --> 07:06.745
<i>Idgie was Buddy's pet
from the day she was born.</i>

07:09.620 --> 07:13.147
<i>I remember the day we was all getting ready
for Leona's wedding.</i>

07:13.260 --> 07:15.183
<i>The war had just ended.</i>

07:15.300 --> 07:16.745
<i>The "Great" one, you know.</i>

07:17.860 --> 07:19.749
<i>And another one was about to begin</i>

07:19.860 --> 07:21.783
<i>in the Threadgoode house.</i>

07:21.900 --> 07:25.143
<i>Sipsey, honey, is that finished?</i>

07:26.300 --> 07:28.348
Oh, Buddy. Buddy, get dressed, honey.

07:28.460 --> 07:30.383
<i>- Mama...</i>
- Leona, what is it?

07:30.500 --> 07:34.550
Idgie's upstairs in her room and she said
she won't come out just as long as she lives.

07:34.660 --> 07:36.788
- Mama, she is gonna ruin my wedding.
- Shh.

07:36.900 --> 07:39.744
Why, Leona,
you're gonna be the most beautiful bride...

07:39.860 --> 07:41.783
Well, of course she is, Papa.

07:43.020 --> 07:46.661
Your papa has spent every last nickel he has
just to make you happy.

07:46.780 --> 07:49.431
Now, you try to act a little grateful, young lady.

07:50.540 --> 07:52.463
Imogen Louise Threadgoode!

07:53.580 --> 07:55.503
This is your mama!

07:58.380 --> 08:00.906
You come down here... right now.

08:01.020 --> 08:02.749
Do you hear me?

08:02.860 --> 08:05.625
- Buddy, you fetch her. She'll listen to you.
- Come on down.

08:05.740 --> 08:07.981
<i>There's no firing squad waiting for you.</i>

08:08.100 --> 08:09.943
Oh...

08:10.060 --> 08:12.347
<i>Come on, honey. Now, let us see you.</i>

08:13.460 --> 08:15.462
<i>Oh, you look so pretty.</i>

08:15.580 --> 08:18.265
- I see London, I see...
<i>- Hush!</i>

08:19.980 --> 08:21.903
Julian, hush.

08:23.340 --> 08:24.466
<i>Come ahead, sweetheart.</i>

08:26.020 --> 08:29.581
<i>You look awful nice in that.</i>

08:29.700 --> 08:31.190
<i>- Mama!</i>
- You look fine, Idgie.

08:31.300 --> 08:34.986
<i>- She looks like a monkey.
- Julian, stop it right this second.</i>

08:35.580 --> 08:37.105
<i>- Take it back!</i>
- Idgie.

08:38.780 --> 08:41.750
I told you she was gonna ruin my wedding!

08:43.020 --> 08:44.943
Take it back! Take it back!

08:47.740 --> 08:49.469
- I'll get you for this.
- No, Buddy.

08:54.780 --> 08:57.943
- <i>Be careful when she's dressing up.</i>
- <i>She's just a pain.</i>

08:58.060 --> 09:02.463
<i>Leona, will you stop shrieking, honey?
This is your wedding day</i>

09:14.700 --> 09:17.385
<i>Looks like you got yourself up a tree, little bit</i>

09:18.500 --> 09:20.343
I'm sick of people making fun of me.

09:20.460 --> 09:22.827
So you're gonna stay up here all day long?

09:22.940 --> 09:24.465
Yep.

09:24.580 --> 09:28.426
The hell with them. Who wants to wear
that stupid old dress anyway?

09:29.940 --> 09:31.942
Did I ever tell you about the oysters?

09:32.060 --> 09:35.030
<i>- Oysters?</i>
- Didn't I tell you about the oysters?

09:35.140 --> 09:39.589
<i>Think about the millions of oysters
lying around on the bottom of the ocean.</i>

09:39.700 --> 09:41.623
Then one day...

09:41.740 --> 09:46.587
God comes along and he sees one and he says,
"I think I'm gonna make that one different."

09:46.700 --> 09:48.623
And you know what he does?

09:49.820 --> 09:51.743
He puts a little piece of sand in it.

09:52.860 --> 09:55.306
And guess what it can do that the others can't.

09:55.420 --> 09:58.185
- What?
- It can make a beautiful pearl.

09:59.980 --> 10:02.267
What if God made a mistake?

10:03.380 --> 10:07.180
Well, the way I figure it,
he never makes mistakes.

10:07.300 --> 10:09.223
I mean, he made sure we got together.

10:09.340 --> 10:13.584
He made sure you got the best-looking,
most charming brother in the world,

10:13.700 --> 10:15.748
who's gonna beat you to the chocolate cake.

10:15.860 --> 10:17.430
You will not.

10:17.540 --> 10:19.747
Got you out of the tree, now, didn't I?

10:20.860 --> 10:22.589
Did not.

10:22.700 --> 10:25.909
<i>Into this estate,
these two people come now to be joined.</i>

10:26.020 --> 10:30.628
<i>If any man present can show cause
why they might not be lawfully joined together,</i>

10:30.740 --> 10:33.983
let him speak now,
or for ever after hold his peace.

10:35.100 --> 10:37.023
Please be seated.

10:40.540 --> 10:42.588
If either of you know any reason

10:42.700 --> 10:45.465
<i>why you may not justly
be joined together in holy matrimony</i>

10:45.580 --> 10:47.947
do you now confess it?

10:57.780 --> 10:59.828
It is in your will to proceed.

11:01.660 --> 11:03.424
<i>Do you, Charles Osgood Justice...</i>

11:08.980 --> 11:12.302
<i>Thank you. I don't know what we'd do
without your generosity.</i>

11:12.420 --> 11:16.220
<i>- Sipsey, honey, look at what you've done.
- You're welcome, Mrs. Threadgoode.</i>

11:17.340 --> 11:19.069
You rascal, you!

11:25.140 --> 11:29.384
<i>I don't think there ever was</i>
<i>a sweeter boy than Buddy Threadgoode.</i>

11:29.500 --> 11:31.229
You look beautiful today, Lily.

11:31.340 --> 11:33.263
Yeah, Lily, you sure do.

11:33.380 --> 11:35.428
<i>I had the biggest crush on him.</i>

11:36.940 --> 11:38.863
<i>He was a terrible ﬂirt</i>

11:38.980 --> 11:41.187
<i>But his heart belonged to Ruth Jamison.</i>

11:42.500 --> 11:45.629
<i>Now, she was the daughter
of a friend of his mama's</i>

11:45.740 --> 11:48.220
<i>who was visiting that summer.</i>

11:48.340 --> 11:51.469
Ruth Jamison,
you're just the one I've been looking for.

11:51.580 --> 11:53.105
Are you thirsty?

11:53.220 --> 11:54.665
Let's go visit someplace else.

12:00.340 --> 12:03.549
If you think that's a big lake,
you should have seen the one by our house.

12:03.660 --> 12:05.583
We used to swim in it and fish.

12:05.700 --> 12:08.271
I sure do miss it. I sure do.

12:08.380 --> 12:10.951
Well, what happened to it? Did it dry up?

12:11.060 --> 12:12.789
No. Worse than that.

12:12.900 --> 12:14.902
Last fall, a big flock of ducks,

12:15.020 --> 12:17.466
about 40 or 50 of them,
landed smack in the middle of it.

12:17.580 --> 12:19.070
While they were sitting in it,

12:19.180 --> 12:22.423
a fluke thing happened.
The temperature dropped so fast

12:22.540 --> 12:25.350
that the whole lake froze in three seconds,
just like that.

12:25.460 --> 12:27.622
And all those poor little ducks. Did it kill them?

12:27.740 --> 12:30.505
No. They flew off and took the lake with them.

12:30.620 --> 12:34.022
Why, to this very day,
that lake is somewhere over in Georgia.

12:35.140 --> 12:37.427
Buddy Threadgoode.

12:48.020 --> 12:51.149
Just come a little closer.
I want to give you something.

12:51.260 --> 12:53.547
<i>Come here.</i>

12:57.260 --> 12:59.183
Whoa!

13:04.260 --> 13:06.627
<i>Hat, where do you think you're going?</i>

13:08.740 --> 13:11.141
Woo-oo! I've got it.

13:11.260 --> 13:13.627
Hold on, Ruth. Hold on a little bit.

13:18.860 --> 13:20.544
<i>It's all right. I've got it.</i>

13:22.620 --> 13:24.270
Come here, you damn hat.

13:24.380 --> 13:26.109
Got it! Oh!

13:26.220 --> 13:27.585
<i>Oh, I meant to do that</i>

13:30.100 --> 13:31.590
I've got it!

13:33.780 --> 13:35.509
<i>Ta-da!</i>

13:37.260 --> 13:38.386
All right.

13:38.500 --> 13:39.626
Damn. Come on.

13:48.980 --> 13:50.550
Come on.

13:50.660 --> 13:52.628
Get off.

13:52.740 --> 13:54.504
Buddy!

13:54.620 --> 13:57.703
<i>- Buddy!
- Buddy Threadgoode!</i>

13:59.340 --> 14:00.865
<i>Buddy!</i>

14:00.980 --> 14:02.630
Get out of there.

14:04.140 --> 14:06.108
Get out of there.

14:07.460 --> 14:08.950
<i>Buddy!</i>

14:11.140 --> 14:13.142
<i>- Run, Buddy!
- Buddy!</i>

14:14.220 --> 14:15.426
Buddy!

14:19.100 --> 14:20.943
No!

14:23.100 --> 14:24.101
<i>Buddy!</i>

14:25.220 --> 14:27.143
<i>No-oo!</i>

14:27.260 --> 14:28.705
<i>No-oo!</i>

14:28.820 --> 14:31.346
<i>Buddy! No!</i>

14:31.460 --> 14:34.384
Please! Let me go!

14:35.860 --> 14:37.385
No.

14:37.500 --> 14:39.423
Buddy!

14:39.540 --> 14:41.463
Come on. We've got to get back to the house.

14:41.580 --> 14:42.991
No, Mama.

14:43.100 --> 14:45.421
<i>Come on. We've got to go home.</i>

14:45.540 --> 14:46.826
Buddy!

14:46.940 --> 14:49.181
- Buddy!
<i>- You have to be strong. It's gonna be OK.</i>

14:49.300 --> 14:51.109
Buddy!

14:51.220 --> 14:53.951
The Lord is my shepherd,

14:54.060 --> 14:56.142
<i>I shall not want.</i>

14:56.260 --> 14:59.025
<i>It like to have killed us all.</i>

14:59.140 --> 15:01.711
<i>But nary a one took it as hard as Idgie.</i>

15:04.700 --> 15:08.421
<i>Everyone thought she'd die right along with him.</i>

15:25.780 --> 15:28.863
<i>Night after night, she stayed by the river.</i>

15:30.060 --> 15:35.942
<i>Big George was the only soul she'd let near her,
and he watched over her night and day.</i>

15:37.620 --> 15:41.864
<i>You know, a heart can be broken,
but it still keeps a-beating just the same.</i>

15:42.980 --> 15:48.225
Miss Idgie, you'll have to keep this blanket on
or you'll catch your death of cold, you hear me?

15:49.580 --> 15:51.503
That's so sad.

16:00.340 --> 16:02.263
Would you like one of these?

16:02.380 --> 16:04.621
Oh! Thank you, honey.

16:04.740 --> 16:06.469
Evelyn...

16:06.580 --> 16:08.503
Honey, we gotta get going.

16:08.620 --> 16:12.591
The Braves game's fixing to start
and you're gonna miss your... thing.

16:12.700 --> 16:14.429
Excuse me.

16:14.540 --> 16:16.269
That's my husband Ed.

16:16.380 --> 16:18.348
Hi, ma'am.

16:18.460 --> 16:20.383
Um...

16:21.740 --> 16:23.742
I can't believe Buddy died.

16:23.860 --> 16:25.783
Neither could I.

16:27.300 --> 16:31.589
Oh, well... I enjoyed talking to you, honey.
What's your name?

16:31.700 --> 16:34.590
Evelyn. Evelyn Couch.

16:34.700 --> 16:36.225
I've got to go.

16:36.340 --> 16:38.263
You come back and see me, you hear?

16:39.340 --> 16:41.263
OK.

16:41.380 --> 16:42.950
Bye-bye.

16:43.420 --> 16:45.422
<i>Well, first of all I want you</i>

16:45.540 --> 16:50.580
<i>to truly dedicate yourselves
to finding little ways to putting that magic,</i>

16:50.700 --> 16:53.624
that spark, back into your marriage.

16:53.740 --> 16:57.950
When we think of romance and marriage,
what is the first thought

16:58.060 --> 16:59.983
<i>that comes into your mind?</i>

17:00.100 --> 17:01.625
Divorce.

17:01.740 --> 17:05.347
Remember when marriage counsellors
told you to wrap yourself in Cellophane

17:05.460 --> 17:07.701
to put a little charge into your marriage?

17:07.819 --> 17:09.742
Do we really pay for these lectures?

17:24.099 --> 17:26.022
♪ O-oh yeah

17:28.540 --> 17:33.706
♪ As I walk this land of broken dreams

17:33.820 --> 17:38.030
♪ I have visions of many things

17:38.940 --> 17:43.025
♪ Happiness is just an illusion...

17:43.140 --> 17:44.949
Evelyn, have you gone insane?

17:45.060 --> 17:48.906
<i>People can see you! What if I'd have been
the paperboy or something, honey?</i>

17:49.020 --> 17:50.670
Get in there.

17:50.780 --> 17:54.102
What were you thinking about?

17:54.220 --> 17:56.143
<i>Evelyn.</i>

17:57.500 --> 17:59.662
- Evelyn!
- Oh.

17:59.780 --> 18:03.421
You know, what we really need,
instead of this baloney,

18:03.540 --> 18:06.828
is an assertiveness training class
for southern women.

18:06.940 --> 18:10.103
But that's a contradiction in terms, isn't it?

18:11.220 --> 18:14.224
Especially you, sweetheart.
You're living in the Dark Ages.

18:15.900 --> 18:20.588
♪ The roots of love grow all around

18:20.700 --> 18:25.183
♪ But for me they come tumbling down

18:25.300 --> 18:30.261
♪ Every day heartaches grow a little stronger

18:30.380 --> 18:35.261
♪ I can't stand this pain much longer...

18:36.660 --> 18:38.822
Hi, honey. I need one of those.

18:38.940 --> 18:40.669
Mm, you smell good, too.

18:40.780 --> 18:42.703
- Thank you.
<i>- I need one of these.</i>

18:43.940 --> 18:45.863
Oh, this looks good.

18:45.980 --> 18:48.028
Yes, indeedy.

18:48.140 --> 18:52.384
♪ Always moving but going nowhere

18:52.500 --> 18:57.222
♪ What becomes of the brokenhearted...

18:57.340 --> 18:59.263
Ed...

19:01.820 --> 19:05.142
Why don't you come in and sit down at the table
and have dinner with me?

19:05.260 --> 19:08.707
I'm sorry, honey. The game's almost over.
I just wanted to see a bit of it.

19:08.820 --> 19:10.549
Why are you so dressed up?

19:10.660 --> 19:13.982
Honey, don't get in the way there.
Just scoot over just a bit.

19:16.700 --> 19:18.225
Ed...

19:18.340 --> 19:23.665
if I'd opened the door wearing only Cellophane,
would you still be watching the baseball game?

19:23.780 --> 19:27.182
No, honey,
I'd probably be checking you into a loony bin.

19:52.140 --> 19:55.064
<i>- Hi, sugar. How's my little dumpling?</i>
- Trick or treat?

19:55.180 --> 19:57.786
<i>You won't throw one of those hissy fits,
will you?</i>

19:57.900 --> 19:59.106
No, no, no!

20:01.340 --> 20:04.742
<i>- You are meaner than a damn snake.
- I'm glad you're feeling better.</i>

20:04.860 --> 20:07.989
<i>- You need to get back in bed.</i>
- Good thing your eyesight's failing.

20:17.740 --> 20:19.663
Hey!

20:19.780 --> 20:22.545
- Hey.
- I was hoping you'd be here.

20:23.660 --> 20:27.710
My roommate, Mrs. Otis, said I could stay
and visit with her and her family,

20:27.820 --> 20:31.666
but I said, "Thank you kindly,
but I think I might have my own visitor."

20:31.780 --> 20:33.703
And here you are!

20:33.820 --> 20:36.141
- Well, now, sit down.
- Thank you.

20:36.260 --> 20:37.989
And doughnuts to boot.

20:38.100 --> 20:39.829
You can't beat that.

20:39.940 --> 20:42.546
Well, help yourself, Mrs. Threadgoode.

20:42.660 --> 20:44.230
How's your friend?

20:44.340 --> 20:46.263
- Mrs. Otis?
- Mm-hm.

20:46.380 --> 20:48.303
Well, not so good.

20:49.420 --> 20:53.345
It looks like I won't be getting home
for quite a while, and I sure miss it.

20:54.860 --> 20:57.466
Funny what you miss
when you're away from home.

20:58.540 --> 21:00.463
I miss the smell of coffee.

21:00.580 --> 21:02.503
And bacon frying.

21:03.620 --> 21:09.582
Oh... what I wouldn't give for a plate of fried
green tomatoes like we used to have at the café.

21:10.700 --> 21:12.623
Ooh...

21:16.900 --> 21:19.187
I never told you about the café, did I?

21:19.300 --> 21:21.223
No, ma'am.

21:21.340 --> 21:22.262
Well...

21:22.380 --> 21:24.303
let me back up a bit.

21:25.700 --> 21:30.149
<i>You see,
Idgie never quite got over losing Buddy.</i>

21:32.980 --> 21:35.870
<i>She hardly ever come home.</i>

21:35.980 --> 21:38.631
<i>Only Big George knew how to find her.</i>

21:40.180 --> 21:41.670
<i>She just didn't seem to care</i>

21:41.780 --> 21:43.703
<i>about anything any more.</i>

21:43.820 --> 21:45.231
<i>And then one summer day</i>

21:45.340 --> 21:48.025
<i>her mama sent for her.</i>

21:48.140 --> 21:52.031
<i>Like they say, God never shuts one door
without opening another.</i>

21:53.140 --> 21:56.223
<i>That was also the day Idgie met Frank Bennett.</i>

21:57.340 --> 21:59.468
<i>The man whose murder got her arrested.</i>

21:59.580 --> 22:01.503
Well, hello there, miss.

22:01.620 --> 22:03.543
And who might you be?

22:04.660 --> 22:06.742
Towanda to you. Who are you?

22:06.860 --> 22:10.785
Oh, Frank Bennett's the name, Miss Towanda.

22:11.900 --> 22:14.346
I must say, you are looking mighty fine today.

22:14.460 --> 22:18.226
Are you a politician,
or does lying just run in your family?

22:21.740 --> 22:24.027
<i>Mama!</i>

22:24.140 --> 22:26.063
There you are!

22:26.180 --> 22:28.103
It's about time, Idgie.

22:31.180 --> 22:33.501
If you don't look like the Wild Man Of Borneo...

22:34.620 --> 22:36.543
- There you go.
- Well, thank you.

22:37.900 --> 22:39.823
- Guess who's here.
- Who?

22:39.940 --> 22:42.420
Ruth. She's staying with us this summer,

22:42.540 --> 22:46.067
and will be in charge of all the young people's
activities at the church.

22:46.180 --> 22:49.627
- Is that why you wanted to see me?
- We have so many nice things planned.

22:49.740 --> 22:50.707
Ruth!

22:52.900 --> 22:54.823
<i>You remember my youngest child?</i>

22:54.940 --> 22:58.228
Of course I do. Hi, Idgie.

22:59.740 --> 23:01.663
Hi.

23:06.340 --> 23:08.581
Maybe this isn't such a good idea.

23:08.700 --> 23:11.101
Oh, it's got to work.

23:11.220 --> 23:13.143
<i>Somebody's got to help her.</i>

23:13.260 --> 23:14.546
<i>I cant.</i>

23:16.060 --> 23:18.870
Are you sure you wanna go
to this here River Club, Miss Ruth?

23:18.980 --> 23:20.630
These ain't no churchgoing folks.

23:20.740 --> 23:22.788
<i>I'll do just fine, George, thank you.</i>

23:24.940 --> 23:29.502
Oh, excuse me.
Is Idgie Threadgoode here, by any chance?

23:29.620 --> 23:31.827
Come on in, honey.
She's right down here.

23:31.940 --> 23:33.863
- Here?
- Uh-huh.

23:35.700 --> 23:37.748
I'll see you, Grady Kilgore.

23:37.860 --> 23:40.227
And I'll raise you 20.

23:40.340 --> 23:42.741
You ain't got nothing.

23:42.860 --> 23:45.101
Maybe I do and maybe I don't.

23:45.220 --> 23:48.588
Put your money where your mouth is,
Mr. Sheriff.

23:54.140 --> 23:56.063
Well, look what the cat brung in.

23:56.180 --> 23:58.103
I came to talk to you.

24:00.620 --> 24:02.622
You're gonna have to wait. I'm busy.

24:02.740 --> 24:05.186
Come on. This is your big chance.
Are you in or out?

24:05.300 --> 24:07.587
<i>It'll make you a rich man.</i>

24:07.700 --> 24:09.190
<i>You're just bluffing, as usual.</i>

24:09.300 --> 24:13.350
I'm afraid you're gonna have to excuse Idgie.
She's going home for dinner.

24:13.460 --> 24:15.701
Nice meeting you. Say goodbye, Idgie.

24:16.820 --> 24:19.869
- Where the hell are you going with my money?
- We're going home.

24:19.980 --> 24:23.666
<i>- Who are you to boss me around?</i>
- I'm the one holding your money, that's who.

24:23.780 --> 24:25.509
Give it back.

24:25.620 --> 24:27.543
Now, get in the car.

24:29.460 --> 24:31.383
All right. I'll get in the car.

24:32.500 --> 24:34.229
You win.

24:35.340 --> 24:37.991
Come on.

24:38.100 --> 24:39.590
Sucker!

24:39.700 --> 24:41.543
<i>I'll leave here when I want to.</i>

24:41.660 --> 24:44.709
I just don't know how you can break
your mother's heart like you do.

24:44.820 --> 24:47.266
I'm not doing anything to my mother.

24:47.380 --> 24:49.826
Oh, no?
Why do you think I'm over here for the summer?

24:49.940 --> 24:53.262
Your mother was worried. She thought
I might be able to talk sense into you,

24:53.380 --> 24:55.303
<i>but you're too busy being selfish.</i>

24:55.420 --> 24:57.104
What are you talking about?

24:58.260 --> 25:00.706
Idgie, you're not the only one who lost Buddy.

25:01.820 --> 25:06.986
We all... miss him, but... turning your back
on your family's not gonna help.

25:09.100 --> 25:11.228
What's he got to do with anything?

25:11.340 --> 25:13.422
<i>It looks like you're the one with the problem</i>

25:13.540 --> 25:15.463
forgetting my brother.

25:19.180 --> 25:21.865
<i>Why, just ten miles away,</i>

25:21.980 --> 25:25.951
<i>down by the river, there lurks a den of the devil!</i>

25:27.060 --> 25:29.461
<i>Where liquor and gambling</i>

25:29.580 --> 25:31.503
<i>and sin abide!</i>

25:32.620 --> 25:36.102
Snakes and serpents.

25:36.220 --> 25:38.222
<i>Hey, Scroggins!</i>

25:38.340 --> 25:42.140
You're finally preaching
about something you're kin to. Snakes!

25:43.260 --> 25:45.308
<i>As I said...</i>

25:45.420 --> 25:50.301
snakes and serpents take many disguises.

25:50.420 --> 25:53.549
<i>Let's turn to page 53 in our hymnal.</i>

25:59.980 --> 26:01.903
Yoo-hoo!

26:02.020 --> 26:05.183
Big George thought I might find you here.

26:09.420 --> 26:11.821
If you give me a chance,

26:11.940 --> 26:13.908
a chance to get to know you,

26:14.020 --> 26:15.943
maybe it'll be fun!

26:17.860 --> 26:19.783
Fun?!

26:20.900 --> 26:23.551
Idgie, just spend some time with me.

26:25.660 --> 26:27.389
- Please.
- Suit yourself.

26:29.460 --> 26:32.304
Are you sure you don't wanna back out?
It's not too late.

26:32.420 --> 26:33.831
I'm sure.

26:34.940 --> 26:36.863
Here, hold this.

26:38.980 --> 26:40.903
Tell me, now, do you like trains?

26:41.020 --> 26:42.545
Y... Yes.

26:42.660 --> 26:44.185
Good.

26:45.300 --> 26:47.428
We'll get along just fine.

26:50.500 --> 26:52.423
Boy, did we luck out tonight!

26:56.140 --> 26:58.063
Hop in.

26:58.180 --> 27:00.103
I..-

27:01.340 --> 27:03.308
Oh... give me your hand.

27:03.420 --> 27:05.548
Put your foot up there.

27:15.940 --> 27:17.863
Hold that.

27:19.660 --> 27:21.185
Look at all this.

27:25.340 --> 27:27.263
I think we should get off the train.

27:27.380 --> 27:29.030
It's starting to move.

27:29.140 --> 27:31.063
No. The fun's just started.

27:35.780 --> 27:37.703
Are you all right?

27:37.820 --> 27:40.949
Well, sometimes I get a little dizzy looking down.

27:42.060 --> 27:43.983
Don't look down.

27:57.540 --> 27:59.463
What are you doing?

27:59.580 --> 28:00.991
Come on. Look.

28:01.100 --> 28:02.829
They're throwing away food!

28:08.060 --> 28:09.983
You talk about give unto others.

28:10.100 --> 28:12.148
Yes, but this food isn't yours to give.

28:13.140 --> 28:15.063
That's church talk.

28:15.180 --> 28:17.706
I've seen those same people
over at church on Sunday

28:17.820 --> 28:22.064
over at the River Club every other night
of the week, doing anything but pray.

28:37.700 --> 28:39.668
<i>More, more!</i>

29:05.580 --> 29:07.821
OK. Time to get off.

29:08.940 --> 29:11.341
We gotta jump.

29:12.620 --> 29:14.748
- Jump?
<i>- Yeah, jump</i>

29:14.860 --> 29:16.862
<i>The next stop is five miles down the tracks.</i>

29:16.980 --> 29:18.903
I won't walk that far back.

29:19.020 --> 29:21.751
Are you crazy?

29:21.860 --> 29:24.067
<i>You're not kidding.</i>

29:24.180 --> 29:26.103
Well...

29:27.420 --> 29:29.343
I give up. Jump...

29:30.460 --> 29:33.270
I'll tell Mama I'm not
a good influence on you...

29:33.380 --> 29:35.508
You'll never jump, will you?

29:37.500 --> 29:39.423
Don't say never to me.

29:49.660 --> 29:50.627
Aargh!

29:51.980 --> 29:54.711
Towanda...!

30:06.940 --> 30:08.180
Are you all right?

30:08.300 --> 30:09.506
I'm fine.

30:11.100 --> 30:13.023
I'm all right.

30:13.140 --> 30:14.062
Ow!

30:15.180 --> 30:17.103
- Does this hurt?
- Ouch!

30:17.220 --> 30:19.143
I guess so.

30:20.260 --> 30:22.308
- We better get you to a doc... doctor.
- Shit!

30:22.420 --> 30:24.343
Which way is it?

30:24.460 --> 30:27.066
About two miles down the tracks.

30:27.180 --> 30:28.625
All right.

30:28.740 --> 30:30.663
Let's go.

30:32.060 --> 30:34.267
You'll never be able to carry me that far.

30:35.380 --> 30:37.303
I know. Never say never.

30:37.420 --> 30:39.343
I'm not carrying you.

30:39.460 --> 30:41.383
We're walking.

30:47.900 --> 30:49.550
<i>Thank you, Julian.</i>

30:49.660 --> 30:52.266
I owe you one.

31:07.300 --> 31:09.701
<i>- Aren't you ready yet?
- What?</i>

31:12.940 --> 31:16.023
This doesn't have anything to do with trains,
does it?

31:17.140 --> 31:18.869
Do you like honey?

31:18.980 --> 31:20.709
Oh, yeah, I like honey.

31:20.820 --> 31:22.345
- Fresh honey?
- Yeah.

31:22.460 --> 31:23.985
Me too.

31:25.100 --> 31:26.431
There it is.

31:27.540 --> 31:29.383
There what is?

31:31.620 --> 31:34.305
<i>You'll see.
Soon enough.</i>

31:38.180 --> 31:40.182
Now... stay here.

31:40.300 --> 31:42.223
No matter what happens,
don't move.

31:43.860 --> 31:45.783
What are you gonna do?

32:56.100 --> 32:58.023
Here you are, madame.
This is for you.

32:58.140 --> 33:00.063
Wh... Why did you do that?

33:00.180 --> 33:02.103
You could have been killed.

33:03.220 --> 33:05.143
I'm sorry.

33:06.700 --> 33:08.623
Don't you want the honey?

33:08.740 --> 33:10.663
I got it just for you.

33:12.180 --> 33:15.707
It's all right. I do it all the time.
I never get stung, honest.

33:18.380 --> 33:20.223
Don't be mad at me, Ruth.

33:21.340 --> 33:24.025
Idgie, I'm not mad at you.

33:24.140 --> 33:26.063
No fooling?

33:34.140 --> 33:35.665
Is it bad, what I did?

33:35.780 --> 33:38.021
No.

33:38.140 --> 33:40.142
I thought I might be crazy or something.

33:40.260 --> 33:42.183
No, no.

33:42.300 --> 33:46.385
No, I've heard there were people
who could charm bees.

33:46.500 --> 33:49.026
I've just never seen it done before today.

33:52.900 --> 33:55.665
You're just a bee charmer, Idgie Threadgoode.

33:55.780 --> 33:57.703
That's what you are.

33:57.820 --> 33:59.549
A bee charmer.

34:00.660 --> 34:03.106
Here. Do you wanna taste it?

34:09.500 --> 34:11.502
Surprise!

34:15.620 --> 34:18.464
- Idgie Threadgoode!
- Tonight we're gonna have a real party.

34:18.580 --> 34:21.106
Drink this
and then we're gonna play some poker.

34:21.219 --> 34:25.145
Well, I don't... I don't know how to play poker
and I never drink, but...

34:25.260 --> 34:26.864
thank you anyway.

34:28.380 --> 34:30.985
♪ Oh, my darlin', oh, my darlin'

34:31.100 --> 34:33.831
Here comes the wind-up now.
Here comes the wind-up.

34:33.940 --> 34:37.069
Burn that ball in here.
Burn 'em in here. Burn 'em in here.

34:37.179 --> 34:39.103
Right in the pocket. Right in the pocket.

34:39.219 --> 34:40.745
I don't know how to bat.

34:40.860 --> 34:43.466
Yeah, and you don't drink either.

34:45.100 --> 34:48.263
- Gonna be a spitter. Gonna be a spitter.
<i>- Hold the bat and swing. I'll pitch it easy to you.</i>

34:48.380 --> 34:51.384
<i>- Spitter? Is she gonna spit at me?
- No, she gonna spit on the ball.</i>

34:52.739 --> 34:54.663
Take another crack at it.

34:54.780 --> 34:56.668
<i>OK. Take another crack at it.</i>

34:56.780 --> 34:59.306
<i>- Get 'em in here. Get 'em in here.
- Get 'em in, come on.</i>

35:01.420 --> 35:03.343
Wooh! Wooh!

35:06.700 --> 35:08.623
You've got to run.

35:09.860 --> 35:11.783
Come on, run.

35:11.900 --> 35:13.629
Don't kiss everybody! Run!

35:14.740 --> 35:18.301
I have never had so much fun in my whole life.

35:18.420 --> 35:21.902
And I even got a home run.

35:22.020 --> 35:23.943
A clean one at that.

35:25.260 --> 35:27.183
A straight beats three of a kind.

35:32.940 --> 35:34.863
You know, poker isn't half bad.

35:37.260 --> 35:41.310
Idgie, what's your mother gonna say
when she sees us both... drunk?

35:42.940 --> 35:45.864
You've got to stop worrying
about what people think.

35:45.980 --> 35:48.381
I mean, you've always done the right thing.

35:48.500 --> 35:51.822
You took care of your daddy, the preacher,
when he took sick.

35:51.940 --> 35:55.501
You take care of all of the kids
over at the church school.

35:55.620 --> 35:57.748
You're gonna take care of your mama.

35:57.860 --> 36:01.706
I know. And I'm gonna marry
the man I'm supposed to.

36:01.820 --> 36:03.549
You're getting married?!

36:03.660 --> 36:05.628
As soon as the summer's over.

36:11.380 --> 36:13.303
Oh, am I gonna miss you!

36:14.980 --> 36:16.903
This is the best birthday...

36:18.140 --> 36:20.029
...I ever had.

36:33.420 --> 36:36.264
<i>Ruth invited Idgie to the wedding,</i>

36:36.380 --> 36:38.587
<i>but Idgie never did write back.</i>

36:38.700 --> 36:40.225
<i>No.</i>

36:40.340 --> 36:43.344
<i>But she did drive all night to Valdosta, Georgia</i>

36:43.460 --> 36:44.950
<i>to watch from afar.</i>

36:45.060 --> 36:46.585
Whoa! Here we go!

36:47.700 --> 36:50.624
<i>And then she swore
she'd never see Ruth again.</i>

36:56.380 --> 36:58.986
Now, Mama Jamison,
you put that down right now.

36:59.100 --> 37:01.580
Oh, my Lord!

37:07.780 --> 37:11.990
<i>So, during these next few weeks,
we will be learning to reclaim</i>

37:12.100 --> 37:13.943
<i>our own power as women.</i>

37:14.060 --> 37:15.983
Hallelujah.

37:16.100 --> 37:17.829
And tonight.

37:17.940 --> 37:22.343
We're gonna begin to explore
our own femaleness

37:22.460 --> 37:27.341
<i>by examining the source of our strength</i>

37:27.460 --> 37:29.383
and our separateness.

37:30.500 --> 37:31.661
Our vaginas.

37:33.540 --> 37:36.191
So, if you all will just slip off your panties now

37:36.300 --> 37:38.223
and straddle your mirrors.

37:39.780 --> 37:42.306
<i>- Oh, I'm so sorry.</i>
<i>- Miss Couch.</i>

37:42.420 --> 37:43.626
Miss Couch!

37:46.420 --> 37:49.390
Um... I need to be excused for a minute.

37:49.500 --> 37:51.309
Um... Missy,

37:51.420 --> 37:53.866
<i>could you come with me to the ladies' room?</i>

37:53.980 --> 37:55.664
Do you find this threatening?

37:55.780 --> 37:57.464
Uh, well...

37:57.580 --> 38:00.186
Do you have a problem with your sexuality?

38:00.300 --> 38:01.540
No, ma'am.

38:01.660 --> 38:04.504
But I do have a problem with my girdle.

38:16.260 --> 38:18.149
♪ Cherish is the word

38:18.260 --> 38:22.424
♪ I use to describe...

38:25.900 --> 38:27.823
Hi, baby.

38:27.940 --> 38:29.863
All right! Fried chicken.

38:29.980 --> 38:31.903
My favourite.

38:37.300 --> 38:39.382
Ed...

38:40.500 --> 38:45.904
Ed, those classes that I've been taking for ever
aren't helping us one bit.

38:47.020 --> 38:48.943
Let's go to Florida,

38:49.060 --> 38:50.983
like when we got married.

38:51.100 --> 38:53.023
Kyle's gone.

38:53.140 --> 38:55.063
Busy with his own life.

38:55.180 --> 38:57.103
It'd be just the two of us.

38:57.220 --> 38:59.268
Honey, it's just the two of us here now.

38:59.380 --> 39:01.906
Boy, you got a good scald on that chicken.

39:02.020 --> 39:04.022
I'm telling you, it's really good.

39:04.140 --> 39:09.670
Thank you. We could rent a boat
and drift around in the hot sun.

39:10.780 --> 39:12.703
What do you think about it?

39:12.820 --> 39:16.029
Well, I'm just getting used to
it being quiet around here.

39:16.140 --> 39:20.464
Honey, if those classes aren't doing you
any good, then don't go to them.

39:25.140 --> 39:27.541
Damn. The game's blacked out.

39:37.340 --> 39:39.183
Oo-hoo! Mrs. Threadgoode?

39:39.300 --> 39:41.029
Hey, Evelyn.

39:42.620 --> 39:44.702
Do you like it?

39:44.820 --> 39:46.743
Oooh!

39:46.860 --> 39:49.181
Well, who did it for you, darling?

39:49.300 --> 39:50.870
<i>Believe it or not,</i>

39:50.980 --> 39:55.429
it was a student, a little bitty thing no bigger
than a midget, from the beauty college.

39:56.540 --> 39:59.464
Sometimes they come out here
and do our hair for free.

39:59.580 --> 40:01.025
Just for the practice, you know?

40:01.140 --> 40:03.063
Is Ed with you?

40:03.180 --> 40:05.103
Oh, um...

40:05.220 --> 40:06.949
No, ma'am.

40:07.060 --> 40:10.303
His aunt said she didn't want visitors any more.
Especially us.

40:10.420 --> 40:12.343
It's a shame.

40:12.460 --> 40:14.383
I know he feels bad.

40:14.500 --> 40:17.470
But... Lord, if he'll talk to me about it.

40:22.140 --> 40:24.063
Oh, thank you!

40:24.180 --> 40:27.263
<i>- Merry Christmas.</i>
- Merry Christmas.

40:28.500 --> 40:30.423
Mrs. Threadgoode...

40:34.620 --> 40:36.543
...how about telling me some more...

40:36.660 --> 40:38.583
about Idgie?

40:38.700 --> 40:40.623
Oh, well, now, let me see.

40:40.740 --> 40:42.663
Where were we?

40:42.780 --> 40:45.101
Ruth had just got married to Frank Bennett.

40:45.220 --> 40:48.144
Wasn't that the man
Idgie was arrested for murdering?

40:48.260 --> 40:50.183
That's right.

40:51.300 --> 40:53.541
After Ruth left,

40:53.660 --> 40:56.709
Idgie just went back to her old ways.

40:56.820 --> 40:59.824
<i>Hanging out with Grady and the boys
at the River Club.</i>

41:01.340 --> 41:05.140
<i>But after a few years,
temptation got the better of her</i>

41:05.260 --> 41:10.061
<i>and she drove all the way to Valdosta, Georgia,
to see how Ruth was doing an' all.</i>

41:11.180 --> 41:12.989
<i>And that's when the trouble began.</i>

41:24.020 --> 41:25.943
<i>- Hi there.</i>
- Yes?

41:26.060 --> 41:27.983
Uh... is Ruth at home?

41:28.100 --> 41:30.546
Who's calling?

41:31.660 --> 41:34.743
You just tell her it's the bee charmer
from Alabama.

41:34.860 --> 41:36.783
Ruth!

41:36.900 --> 41:39.790
There's some bee person here to see you.

41:53.820 --> 41:55.743
- Idgie...

41:56.860 --> 41:58.783
You've got a real nice home.

41:58.900 --> 42:00.823
Real nice things an' all.

42:00.940 --> 42:02.783
Thank you.

42:03.900 --> 42:06.028
Oh, Mama said to give you this pie.

42:06.140 --> 42:08.063
So...

42:12.900 --> 42:15.062
Idgie Threadgoode... how are you?

42:16.820 --> 42:18.743
You look so...

42:18.860 --> 42:21.101
so grown-up.

42:22.900 --> 42:25.551
All the guys must be wild about you.

42:25.660 --> 42:27.389
Tell me...

42:27.500 --> 42:29.229
do you have a fella yet?

42:29.340 --> 42:31.263
Uh...

42:31.380 --> 42:33.303
A couple.

42:33.420 --> 42:35.343
I haven't decided on any.

42:35.460 --> 42:37.383
Grady's the most persistent...

42:37.500 --> 42:40.663
<i>- Grady Kilgore?</i>
- Don't say it so loud.

42:40.780 --> 42:42.782
<i>Ruth, honey, who's down there?</i>

42:44.620 --> 42:46.145
Hey...

42:46.260 --> 42:48.183
<i>- What happened to you?</i>
- Nothing.

42:48.300 --> 42:50.382
Nothing. Where d'you get the shiner?

42:50.500 --> 42:51.831
- Well...
<i>- Who's down there?</i>

